<subSubSection pageId="66" pageNumber="67" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1437,151,1581]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,476,501]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Description.</emphasis>
Large cup-shaped, symmetrical or low, flat and irregular sponge (
<figureCitation box="[1148,1236,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="65.[151,250,1971,1993]" captionTargetBox="[208,1378,193,1950]" captionTargetId="figure@65.[208,1378,193,1950]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="FIGURE 29. Psammocinia cf. arenosa (Lendenfeld, 1888). A-E. In situ; F-H. Skeletal architecture (F, x5; G, x10, H, 40)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2651508/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
A–E). Cup-shape sponge attached to the substratum by a narrow base. Walls of cups of uniform thickness. Surface rugose and undulating with upper side many small randomly scattered ostia visible, ± 
<quantity box="[984,1070,548,573]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
in diameter. Texture firm, heavy crust of very fine sand present, non-compressible, difficult to tear. Colour in life dark grey-black; in preservative grey.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1437,151,1581]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,302,655,680]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Skeleton</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[317,397,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="65.[151,250,1971,1993]" captionTargetBox="[208,1378,193,1950]" captionTargetId="figure@65.[208,1378,193,1950]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="FIGURE 29. Psammocinia cf. arenosa (Lendenfeld, 1888). A-E. In situ; F-H. Skeletal architecture (F, x5; G, x10, H, 40)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2651508/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
F–H). Choanosomal skeleton consists of irregular primary fibres cored with foreign material, 320 (260–410) µm in diameter. Secondary fibres are fasciculate, 96 (43–135) µm in diameter, cored near the ectosome, and connected by wide areas of spongin. A secondary web of spongin is found in the choanosome with perforations. A dense mass of fine collagenous filaments, each enlarged terminally at both ends, occurs in the mesohyl.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1437,151,1581]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,661,836,861]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Substratum, depth range and ecology.</emphasis>
Found growing in coral rubble, in and around areas of sand, depth range 
<quantity box="[220,319,872,896]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" metricValueMax="3.4" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" unit="m" value="23.0" valueMax="34.0" valueMin="12.0">12–34 m</quantity>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1437,151,1581]" box="[199,938,908,933]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,499,908,933]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Geographic Distribution.</emphasis>
South and East coasts of 
<collectingCountry box="[787,934,908,933]" name="South Africa" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">South Africa</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="66" pageNumber="67" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1437,151,1581]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,943,968]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lendenfeld" authorityYear="1889" box="[324,476,945,968]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Psammocinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[324,476,945,968]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Psammocinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species possess a sand-armoured surface, a pronounced organized sandy ectosome, and a regular, reticular fibre skeleton, with a hierarchy of concentrically laminated primary and secondary fibres (
<bibRefCitation author="Cook and Bergquist" box="[158,449,1015,1040]" firstAuthor="Cook" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="399 - 426" refId="ref42472" refString="Cook, S. de C. &amp; Bergquist, P. R. (1998) Revision of the genus Psammocinia (Porifera: Demospongiae: Dictyoceratida), with six new species from New Zealand. New Zealand Journal of Marine and Freshwater Research, 32, 399 - 426. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00288330.1998.9516834" type="journal article" year="1998">Cook and Bergquist 1998</bibRefCitation>
). The genus consists of 19 species distributed mainly in the Indo-Pacific and 
<collectingCountry box="[1311,1383,1016,1039]" name="South Korea" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Korea</collectingCountry>
. The sponge described here agrees well with the description of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lendenfeld" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[812,930,1053,1076]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Psammocinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="arenosa">
<emphasis box="[812,930,1053,1076]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">P. arenosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Cook &amp; Bergquist" box="[1083,1373,1052,1077]" firstAuthor="Cook" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="399 - 426" refId="ref42472" refString="Cook, S. de C. &amp; Bergquist, P. R. (1998) Revision of the genus Psammocinia (Porifera: Demospongiae: Dictyoceratida), with six new species from New Zealand. New Zealand Journal of Marine and Freshwater Research, 32, 399 - 426. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00288330.1998.9516834" type="journal article" year="1998">Cook &amp; Bergquist (1998)</bibRefCitation>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[151,254,1087,1112]" name="Australia" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Australia</collectingCountry>
and that of 
<bibRefCitation author="Kirkpatrick" box="[390,601,1087,1112]" firstAuthor="Kirkpatrick" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="233 - 264" refId="ref46065" refString="Kirkpatrick, R. (1903) Descriptions of South African sponges. Part III. Cape of Good Hope, Department of Agriculture Bulletin. Marine investigations in South Africa, 2 (16), 233 - 264." type="journal article" year="1903">Kirkpatrick (1903)</bibRefCitation>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[671,819,1087,1112]" name="South Africa" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">South Africa</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lendenfeld" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[830,1079,1089,1112]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Psammocinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="arenosa">
<emphasis box="[830,1079,1089,1112]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Psammocinia arenosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are cup-shaped, attached to the substratum with a narrow base, have walls of uniform thickness and are incompressible with a thick crust of sand. Their description of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lendenfeld" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[399,522,1161,1184]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Psammocinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="arenosa">
<emphasis box="[399,522,1161,1184]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">P. arenosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’s skeleton included irregular cored primary fibres, 
<quantity box="[1142,1236,1160,1185]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" unit="mm" value="200.0">200 µm</quantity>
in diameter and secondary fibres, 
<quantity box="[360,438,1196,1221]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" unit="mm" value="50.0">50 µm</quantity>
in diameter, which may show coring. This is similar to the sponge described here. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Cook &amp; Bergquist, 1998)" authorityName="Cook &amp; Bergquist" authorityYear="1998" baseAuthorityName="Cook &amp; Bergquist" baseAuthorityYear="1998" box="[151,702,1231,1256]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Psammocinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="amodes">
<emphasis box="[151,396,1231,1256]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Psammocinia amodes</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Cook &amp; Bergquist" box="[413,694,1231,1256]" firstAuthor="Cook" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="399 - 426" refId="ref42472" refString="Cook, S. de C. &amp; Bergquist, P. R. (1998) Revision of the genus Psammocinia (Porifera: Demospongiae: Dictyoceratida), with six new species from New Zealand. New Zealand Journal of Marine and Freshwater Research, 32, 399 - 426. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00288330.1998.9516834" type="journal article" year="1998">Cook &amp; Bergquist, 1998</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lendenfeld" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[853,971,1233,1256]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Psammocinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="arenosa">
<emphasis box="[853,971,1233,1256]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">P. arenosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but is distinguished by thin sand armour and a digitate to spatulate form (
<bibRefCitation author="Cook &amp; Bergquist" box="[524,803,1268,1293]" firstAuthor="Cook" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="399 - 426" refId="ref42472" refString="Cook, S. de C. &amp; Bergquist, P. R. (1998) Revision of the genus Psammocinia (Porifera: Demospongiae: Dictyoceratida), with six new species from New Zealand. New Zealand Journal of Marine and Freshwater Research, 32, 399 - 426. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00288330.1998.9516834" type="journal article" year="1998">Cook &amp; Bergquist 1998</bibRefCitation>
). Classifying this sponge fully as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lendenfeld" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[1191,1310,1269,1292]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Psammocinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="arenosa">
<emphasis box="[1191,1310,1269,1292]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">P. arenosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is difficult due to its distribution in 
<collectingCountry box="[428,576,1303,1328]" name="South Africa" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">South Africa</collectingCountry>
. No other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lendenfeld" authorityYear="1889" box="[693,845,1305,1328]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Psammocinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[693,845,1305,1328]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Psammocinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are described here or in the WIO. Due to its similarity to 
<emphasis box="[294,417,1341,1364]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lendenfeld" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[294,413,1341,1364]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Psammocinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="arenosa">P. arenosa</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
this sponge is regarded as 
<taxonomicName box="[719,1000,1340,1365]" class="Demospongiae" family="Irciniidae" genus="Psammocina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dictyoceratida" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="arenosa">
<emphasis box="[719,864,1341,1364]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Psammocina</emphasis>
cf. 
<emphasis box="[907,1000,1341,1364]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">arenosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[1000,1004,1341,1364]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
